## Why This Is Asked
Tests practical use of least-privilege cross-service access in a private subnet, combining IAM roles, S3 bucket policies, and VPC endpoints.

## Key Concepts
- IAM roles attached to EC2 instances
- S3 bucket policies with source VPCE conditions
- VPC endpoints and route tables for private access
- Deny/Allow policy composition and testing

## Code Example
```json
// EC2 role (conceptual)
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {"Effect": "Allow", "Action": "s3:GetObject", "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::config-bucket/config.json"}
  ]
}
```
```json
// VPCE policy (conceptual)
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Action": ["s3:GetObject"],
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::config-bucket/config.json",
      "Condition": {"StringEquals": {"aws:SourceVpce": "vpce-12345"}}
    }
  ]
}
```
```json
// Bucket policy (conceptual)
{
  "Version": "2012-10-17",
  "Statement": [
    {
      "Effect": "Deny",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": "s3:*",
      "Resource": ["arn:aws:s3:::config-bucket", "arn:aws:s3:::config-bucket/*"],
      "Condition": {"StringNotEquals": {"aws:SourceVpce": "vpce-12345"}}
    },
    {
      "Effect": "Allow",
      "Principal": "*",
      "Action": "s3:GetObject",
      "Resource": "arn:aws:s3:::config-bucket/config.json",
      "Condition": {"StringEquals": {"aws:SourceVpce": "vpce-12345"}}
    }
  ]
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you extend this to support multiple config files or buckets?
- How would you monitor and alert on VPCE policy misconfigurations?

## Why This Is Asked
Assesses design of scalable, compliant pipelines with immutability, latency, DR, and cost in AWS.

## Key Concepts
- Kinesis Firehose, S3, Object Lock, SSE-KMS
- Glue Streaming, Lambda, DynamoDB state
- DLQ, cross-region replication, CloudWatch

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-idempotent Lambda sketch
const AWS = require('aws-sdk');
const ddb = new AWS.DynamoDB.DocumentClient();
exports.handler = async (evt) => {
  const key = { id: evt.id };
  const exists = await ddb.get({TableName:'Processed', Key:key}).promise();
  if (exists.Item) return;
  await ddb.put({TableName:'Processed', Item:{id: evt.id, t: Date.now()}}).promise();
  // enrich data
};
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you validate data quality and schema evolution across regions?
- How do you handle late-arriving data and reprocessing without duplicating work?
